WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:02.794
<i>So what's next, podcast-wise?</i>

00:04.504 --> 00:06.881
<i>What we need is a hot, fresh, dead body,</i>

00:06.881 --> 00:09.342
preferably right here
or very near to here.

00:09.342 --> 00:12.178
I got another email from that Bev Melon.

00:12.178 --> 00:14.389
They wanna make a movie of our podcast.

00:14.389 --> 00:16.891
- Paramount?
- They wanna fly us all out to LA

00:16.891 --> 00:19.144
for some meeting next week.

00:19.144 --> 00:20.645
Let's talk movies!

00:21.021 --> 00:22.814
<i>I invited Sazz to the party,</i>

00:22.814 --> 00:25.442
but she's back to not responding
and she usually gets right back to me.

00:25.442 --> 00:28.278
<i>She had something "sensitive"
to discuss with me.</i>

00:28.278 --> 00:31.114
She's had so many joints
replaced by metal.

00:31.114 --> 00:33.450
Apparently, the best ones
come from Bulgaria.

00:33.450 --> 00:34.826
What's all this?

00:35.160 --> 00:37.287
[on phone] <i>You need
your kitchen window replaced.</i>

00:37.287 --> 00:39.622
<i>Something left a little hole.</i>

00:39.622 --> 00:40.707
<i>Like a bullet hole?</i>

00:52.886 --> 00:54.888
<i>Okay, make-- Yeah. Mm-hmm.</i>

00:54.888 --> 00:56.347
<i>Well, hold on there.</i>

00:56.347 --> 00:59.142
<i>Stunt people are not actually daredevils.</i>

00:59.142 --> 01:01.227
Sure, we find danger sexy.

01:01.853 --> 01:03.480
You know, we like to flirt with it,

01:03.480 --> 01:04.773
buy it a drink,

01:04.773 --> 01:08.818
but we don't let it get into our pants.
You know?

01:08.818 --> 01:11.154
We do danger safely.

01:11.154 --> 01:12.781
So, if we do get hurt,

01:12.781 --> 01:15.033
we live to fall another day.

01:16.534 --> 01:18.495
You know who taught me that?

01:18.495 --> 01:21.456
The best stuntman in the world.

01:21.456 --> 01:25.126
My old man, Slim Pataki.

01:26.961 --> 01:29.422
<i>I come from a long line of stunt people.</i>
Are you ready?

01:29.422 --> 01:30.632
Yeah!
- Here we go!

01:30.632 --> 01:32.425
<i>You know,
while most parents are trying</i>

01:32.425 --> 01:33.968
<i>to keep their kids away from danger...</i>

01:33.968 --> 01:35.553
Oh!

01:35.553 --> 01:38.014
<i>...mine taught me how to play in it.
Honest to God.</i>

01:38.640 --> 01:40.391
Again, again, again!

01:40.391 --> 01:43.144
<i>There's no point in trying not to fall.</i>

01:43.144 --> 01:46.106
You always fall.
But the trick is

01:46.106 --> 01:48.900
you get up, you dust yourself off,

01:48.900 --> 01:52.821
and make sure you don't become dust.

01:54.531 --> 01:57.117
Charles, are you okay?

01:58.451 --> 02:01.246
What do you need? We're here.

02:03.123 --> 02:04.165
What do I do?

02:05.792 --> 02:07.502
I can't wash her down the drain! Ah!

02:08.503 --> 02:10.505
M-Maybe we could...

02:10.505 --> 02:12.173
get a wipe?

02:12.173 --> 02:15.426
Yes. Yes, a nice, respectful wipe.

02:15.426 --> 02:18.138
Sazz can't end up on a wipe.

02:18.138 --> 02:20.515
Well, you could just leave them like that.

02:21.641 --> 02:24.394
Then, you'd have permanent
Sazz hands.

02:27.230 --> 02:28.731
I'd like to take that one back.

02:30.650 --> 02:32.026
I'm gonna call the police.

02:32.026 --> 02:33.236
- Okay.
- Great. Yeah.

02:40.660 --> 02:42.245
- Do you want me to--
- No.

02:44.539 --> 02:46.374
I know what I'll do.

02:46.374 --> 02:47.959
I'll wash her into a bowl.

02:47.959 --> 02:49.210
- Great plan.
- A bowl!

02:49.210 --> 02:52.255
Then, I can take the water and ashes,
pour 'em into something,

02:52.255 --> 02:54.382
let the water evaporate.

02:54.382 --> 02:56.092
Maybe a Mason jar!

02:56.092 --> 02:58.636
- Oh, homey. Cozy. What a good-- That--
- Yes, a Mason jar.

02:58.636 --> 03:01.848
- I love Mason jars.
- And we will go get that for you now.

03:01.848 --> 03:02.932
Yes.

03:12.233 --> 03:13.776
Sazz...

03:35.715 --> 03:37.425
Ah!

04:03.409 --> 04:05.828
Hey, hey, hey, don't sweat it.

04:07.956 --> 04:09.999
Me being dead is
the least of your <i>problemos.</i>

04:09.999 --> 04:12.794
Also, get your hands off my boobs.

05:02.844 --> 05:05.263
<i>Um...</i>

05:09.892 --> 05:13.187
Oh, God, she's all over me, too!

05:13.187 --> 05:15.356
'Course this is the week my dry cleaner
bumps up his pricing.

05:15.356 --> 05:19.360
Oliver, will you stop shaking Sazz
onto the floor and line up the shot?

05:19.360 --> 05:21.863
Oh, yeah, sorry, sorry.
O-Okay. So-- Alright.

05:21.863 --> 05:25.491
So, if that's where Sazz was hit,

05:25.491 --> 05:28.244
then the angle puts the shooter

05:28.244 --> 05:29.746
in the corner apartment across the way.

05:29.746 --> 05:31.706
But, what if...

05:31.706 --> 05:33.958
she was shot here and then fell?

05:34.375 --> 05:37.003
Then, she was shot by the--

05:37.003 --> 05:39.339
the window next door.
Okay!

05:39.339 --> 05:41.132
My hands are clean.

05:41.132 --> 05:43.051
Sazz is in the jar,

05:43.051 --> 05:44.177
not in this room.

05:44.594 --> 05:46.095
I'm gonna put her right here.

05:46.095 --> 05:47.764
Okay, s-- Wait, no!

05:47.764 --> 05:49.307
I'm gonna put her here

05:49.307 --> 05:51.684
because Sazz used to love
sitting on this counter.

05:51.684 --> 05:53.061
So, this is absolutely--

05:53.061 --> 05:54.562
Unless we put her over--

05:54.562 --> 05:57.148
No, this is good.
This is absolutely good

05:57.148 --> 05:59.817
because it is time to enact protocol.

05:59.817 --> 06:01.152
Let's call the police.

06:01.152 --> 06:03.363
- Hold on! Hold on.
- Wait! I mean,

06:03.363 --> 06:06.908
- yes, do what you need to do.
- Whatever you need.

06:06.908 --> 06:09.285
Absolutely, Charles.
It's just that we thought

06:09.285 --> 06:12.288
maybe we could talk to some people

06:12.288 --> 06:14.791
before the whole building...

06:14.791 --> 06:16.834
comes under siege.

06:19.170 --> 06:22.131
Okay. What do we know so far?

06:22.131 --> 06:25.843
Okay, so Sazz came up here for the wine.

06:25.843 --> 06:28.679
There's a bullet hole in the glass.

06:28.679 --> 06:31.140
And I found a couple of shards
on the window seal,

06:31.140 --> 06:33.810
so it seems the bullet came in, not out.

06:33.810 --> 06:37.188
And also, Howard's cadaver dog
thinks there was a body about here,

06:37.188 --> 06:38.815
and then dragged to the trash chute

06:38.815 --> 06:40.942
by someone who had
access to your apartment,

06:40.942 --> 06:42.860
which is terrifying.

06:42.860 --> 06:45.863
And we know we found
Sazz in the incinerator.

06:45.863 --> 06:47.698
Poor Sazz.

06:47.698 --> 06:48.783
Poor Sazz.

06:48.783 --> 06:51.702
I wish I had something to add,
but I'm just a manifestation

06:51.702 --> 06:54.872
of your rapidly declining
mental state, so...

06:55.498 --> 06:58.000
The shot came from the West Tower,

06:58.000 --> 07:00.628
probably somewhere
across on the 14th floor.

07:00.628 --> 07:03.172
But we need to know
exactly where the body was

07:03.172 --> 07:04.841
to know which apartment.

07:04.841 --> 07:08.261
Oh! We could Luminol the floors!
I could Postmates us a bottle.

07:08.261 --> 07:09.345
Yes!

07:09.345 --> 07:12.014
A-And what is Luminol,
my little murder nerds?

07:12.014 --> 07:14.434
It's a chemical that makes
blood glow in the dark.

07:14.434 --> 07:18.104
Also, other bodily fluids.
That's how I found out

07:18.104 --> 07:20.398
what the construction workers
were doing in my old apartment.

07:20.398 --> 07:21.649
Ew.

07:21.649 --> 07:24.902
I don't get it. Who would kill Sazz?
Everybody loves Sazz.

07:25.570 --> 07:27.947
Well, remember,

07:27.947 --> 07:30.992
the shooter was in the Arconia,

07:30.992 --> 07:33.536
focusing on... your apartment.

07:33.536 --> 07:36.581
And they shot a person dressed like you

07:36.581 --> 07:38.082
in your kitchen.

07:38.082 --> 07:39.500
You see where this is going!

07:39.500 --> 07:41.711
I see where this is going!

07:41.711 --> 07:43.337
You think I was the target?

07:43.337 --> 07:44.630
That's preposterous!

07:44.630 --> 07:48.259
I was <i>People</i> magazine's
8th Most Beloved TV Cop!

07:48.259 --> 07:50.136
In 1989.

07:50.136 --> 07:51.262
'91.

07:51.262 --> 07:52.346
Hmm.

07:52.763 --> 07:55.725
Okay, clearly Sazz was
into something weird,

07:55.725 --> 07:58.895
but what about these notes
we found in her apartment?

07:58.895 --> 08:01.606
You got-- Look, look.
"Sick pup."

08:01.606 --> 08:03.691
This one just has random numbers.

08:03.691 --> 08:05.735
Yeah.
-"Dudenoff."

08:06.611 --> 08:08.446
No idea what that means.

08:09.614 --> 08:12.909
"Looking at Charles."

08:12.909 --> 08:16.287
It's a mistake to make assumptions
this early in an investigation.

08:16.287 --> 08:18.039
Don't let them get in your head.

08:18.039 --> 08:19.207
If you were the target,

08:19.207 --> 08:20.833
it means I was killed because of you,

08:20.833 --> 08:23.419
and that kind of guilt will paralyze you.

08:23.419 --> 08:25.004
We don't know who the target was!

08:27.798 --> 08:28.925
Listen,

08:28.925 --> 08:31.969
buddy, m-maybe we make lists of people

08:31.969 --> 08:35.181
who, uh, hate you
and people who hated Sazz.

08:35.181 --> 08:38.142
Might be fastest to start with Sazz.

08:38.142 --> 08:39.644
Ah...

08:39.644 --> 08:42.855
Sazz was dating Jan, a convicted murderer,

08:42.855 --> 08:45.191
and Sazz said she needed
to break up with Jan.

08:45.191 --> 08:48.152
And we know what Jan does to
people who break up with her.

08:48.152 --> 08:50.488
Okay, but Jan is in prison,

08:50.488 --> 08:52.949
and you broke up with her, too.

08:53.449 --> 08:55.826
Right. I'm calling 911.

08:55.826 --> 08:58.079
It's been a week, and Sazz's
Bulgarian left shoulder and knee

08:58.079 --> 08:59.622
are still in that incinerator.

09:01.874 --> 09:03.876
<i>911. Are you in immediate danger?</i>

09:03.876 --> 09:05.920
No! There's no proof of that!

09:05.920 --> 09:08.130
<i>Alright, then please hold.</i>

09:08.130 --> 09:09.715
<i>Thank you for calling 911.</i>

09:09.715 --> 09:13.302
<i>There are... 68...
emergencies ahead of you.</i>

09:13.302 --> 09:15.054
Sixty-eight!

09:15.054 --> 09:19.517
Okay, it looks like our glorious city
has given us a minute.

09:19.517 --> 09:22.228
Why don't we talk through
what we know about the residents

09:22.228 --> 09:23.980
of the West Tower?

09:24.981 --> 09:26.232
Ah...

09:27.108 --> 09:30.111
The Westies.

09:31.153 --> 09:33.656
They're an odd bunch. Weirdos.

09:33.656 --> 09:35.241
Loners.

09:35.241 --> 09:36.492
Renters.

09:37.285 --> 09:38.661
You don't have to say it like that.

09:38.661 --> 09:40.955
Yeah, boomer,
not everyone was alive

09:40.955 --> 09:43.833
when an apartment cost a bag of beans.

09:43.833 --> 09:45.501
I'd kill to rent anything.

09:45.501 --> 09:49.046
Alright, Charles.
Tell us about the Westies

09:49.755 --> 09:52.592
and why they might, for argument's sake,

09:52.592 --> 09:54.218
want you dead.

09:54.218 --> 09:55.886
There's Stink-Eye Joe.

09:56.971 --> 09:58.598
Seems hostile.

09:58.598 --> 10:00.600
Always looking over here,

10:00.600 --> 10:03.019
giving me the stink-eye.

10:04.562 --> 10:05.563
Ah.

10:05.563 --> 10:07.857
There's the Sauce Family.

10:07.857 --> 10:10.526
Always stirring some kind of sauce

10:10.526 --> 10:12.612
at all hours

10:12.612 --> 10:14.864
and looking over here.

10:14.864 --> 10:17.783
Three people, lots of pots,

10:17.783 --> 10:20.494
always stirring.

10:20.494 --> 10:23.706
Are they stirring up
a nice batch o' murder?

10:23.706 --> 10:25.583
There's the oddest one of all.

10:25.583 --> 10:27.918
Christmas-all-the-Time Guy.

10:27.918 --> 10:30.129
Handsome guy, always working out.

10:30.129 --> 10:33.090
Never takes down
his Christmas decorations.

10:33.090 --> 10:36.177
Wears a Christmas sweater all-year-round.

10:36.886 --> 10:39.555
That's most of the floor I can see.

10:39.555 --> 10:43.351
Besides that one apartment
that never opens its blinds.

10:44.310 --> 10:47.146
I see the lights go on and off sometimes,

10:47.146 --> 10:49.148
but I never see anyone in there.

10:50.107 --> 10:51.484
Interesting.

10:51.484 --> 10:53.944
Okay, let's sniff around
before the cops come.

10:53.944 --> 10:56.781
I think we have to go down
around the block to get in, right?

10:56.781 --> 10:59.659
That's right. They sealed off
the West Tower from the real Arconia

10:59.659 --> 11:01.285
after a Westie opened a brothel.

11:01.285 --> 11:02.578
Pretty good one, too.

11:03.496 --> 11:06.874
Okay, Charles, text us when 911 picks up.

11:06.874 --> 11:08.250
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

11:08.250 --> 11:11.170
Sazz was my stunt double.
I wanna investigate.

11:11.170 --> 11:12.630
Listen,

11:12.630 --> 11:16.008
I know we don't know who the target was,

11:16.008 --> 11:17.677
but just to be safe,

11:17.677 --> 11:19.929
why don't you help out in here?

11:19.929 --> 11:23.015
With the blinds closed.
Stay on hold.

11:23.015 --> 11:26.644
Make a new murder board.
Um, Postmates the Luminol.

11:26.644 --> 11:29.563
Luminol! Postmates.

11:29.563 --> 11:31.941
It was the most technical we'd ever been.

11:33.401 --> 11:36.737
You know this is all happening.
We might as well just get started.

11:41.826 --> 11:42.827
Hey!

11:42.827 --> 11:44.745
You're giving me busy work!

11:44.745 --> 11:48.624
Charles, this is a big job.
We need you to stay safe in here.

11:48.624 --> 11:49.875
- And stay on hold.
- Yeah.

11:49.875 --> 11:51.502
- You don't need to go out there to help.
- Right.

11:51.502 --> 11:53.379
'Course, they tried to shoot you in here.

11:53.379 --> 11:55.256
I was not the target!

11:56.424 --> 11:58.342
Of course, you weren't!

11:58.342 --> 12:01.095
But deadbolt the door.
The killer might have had a key.

12:01.095 --> 12:02.722
We love you, buddy.

12:02.722 --> 12:04.598
We do.

12:04.598 --> 12:06.684
I want to have said that.

12:11.230 --> 12:12.732
Charles, deadbolt!

12:16.694 --> 12:19.655
Okay, he is talking to no one.

12:19.655 --> 12:21.991
Hey, I've talked to
a few dead people before.

12:21.991 --> 12:24.910
Hey, I once invented a whole Fosse number
of you and Charles dancing.

12:24.910 --> 12:27.496
- You had better gams.
- Hey, what's that?

12:27.913 --> 12:29.039
"Building meeting tonight.

12:29.039 --> 12:31.709
"Keep our home from being overrun

12:31.709 --> 12:33.210
by a Hollywood movie shoot."

12:33.210 --> 12:35.671
No, no, no, no.
This movie has to happen.

12:35.671 --> 12:39.675
It's the only way I can keep up
with my sexy, successful girlfriend.

12:39.675 --> 12:43.095
Also, did you know Loretta's
co-star is internet famous

12:43.095 --> 12:45.973
for something called
a "Jon Hamm-in-the-pants situation"?

12:45.973 --> 12:48.559
Oh, I know.
Went deep down that rabbit hole

12:48.559 --> 12:50.644
one rainy afternoon.

12:50.644 --> 12:52.188
<i>Gates of Heaven.</i>

12:52.188 --> 12:53.981
<i>You ever seen it?
It's the first time</i>

12:53.981 --> 12:56.358
<i>I ever saw real people
just being themselves</i>

12:56.358 --> 12:58.819
<i>and being worthy as characters, too.</i>

12:58.819 --> 13:01.947
It was about pet cemeteries.

13:01.947 --> 13:04.074
But with some...

13:04.074 --> 13:07.453
deep existential shit about the afterlife.

13:07.912 --> 13:10.331
<i>And not for the dead so much, I really--</i>

13:10.331 --> 13:12.541
You've been on film hundreds of times,

13:12.541 --> 13:15.085
and the only way the world
will remember your face

13:15.085 --> 13:16.420
is on this old documentary.

13:16.420 --> 13:18.297
Well,

13:18.297 --> 13:21.550
being on film is not
the only way to be remembered.

13:23.761 --> 13:26.722
You know, even if you were the target,

13:27.640 --> 13:29.850
you don't have to feel bad.

13:29.850 --> 13:31.352
That's the gig.

13:31.352 --> 13:33.187
I take hits for my guy.

13:38.275 --> 13:40.861
They're just trying to scare me.

13:40.861 --> 13:42.696
I'm not gonna get scared
in my own apart--

13:46.784 --> 13:48.035
Closet.

13:48.869 --> 13:51.372
Don't know why I'm whispering.
I'm just your subconscious.

14:06.262 --> 14:07.263
Hello, Charles.

14:11.725 --> 14:14.019
Yep. She's real.

14:19.692 --> 14:22.820
Wow... The West Tower.

14:24.446 --> 14:28.075
Somewhere in this pit lay a sniper's nest.

14:28.075 --> 14:31.203
Okay, this is our one chance
to meet people casually

14:31.203 --> 14:34.164
before the cops put everyone on alert.

14:34.164 --> 14:36.625
So, let's look out some windows and chat.

14:36.625 --> 14:38.794
- Look for the weird.
- Okay, first up,

14:38.794 --> 14:41.714
the menacing Stink-Eye Joe.

14:43.507 --> 14:46.302
Okay.

14:48.470 --> 14:50.764
Hey!

14:50.764 --> 14:54.143
It's the famous podcasters
from the East Tower!

14:54.143 --> 14:57.479
- Why, yes, that's us.
- Uh, hi, I'm Mabel.

14:57.479 --> 14:59.064
I don't know if you're aware,

14:59.064 --> 15:01.817
but they're going to be shooting
a movie here based on our podcast.

15:01.817 --> 15:04.528
A movie?
Yes, major stars. Very exciting.

15:04.528 --> 15:06.864
So we're scouting possible
locations to shoot from.

15:06.864 --> 15:09.074
- In! To shoot in.
- Exactly.

15:09.074 --> 15:11.327
With cameras.
N-N-Not bang-bang shoot.

15:11.327 --> 15:12.411
Yeah.

15:12.411 --> 15:14.538
So would you be interested
in showing us your apartment?

15:14.538 --> 15:17.541
Oh, yeah! I love the movies!

15:17.541 --> 15:20.252
I'll show you anything you want!
Come on in!

15:22.630 --> 15:24.214
Vince Fish.

15:24.214 --> 15:27.384
Listen, I got to apologize
for the eye patch.

15:27.384 --> 15:29.803
I have antibiotic-resistant pink eye,

15:29.803 --> 15:32.806
and it leaves one eye,
and then goes back into the other,

15:32.806 --> 15:34.642
and then back and forth
and back and forth like a--

15:34.642 --> 15:37.394
like a virus playing hopscotch!
Anyhoo...

15:37.394 --> 15:39.438
I gotta put a compress on it,

15:39.438 --> 15:41.523
but I don't like to hold it in my hands

15:41.523 --> 15:44.860
because I'm highly contagious, okay?

15:44.860 --> 15:46.612
So, I came up with this system!

15:46.612 --> 15:48.656
- Ah, pink eye. Yes.
- That's a good idea.

15:48.656 --> 15:50.741
S-So, would you mind if
we glance out your window

15:50.741 --> 15:52.868
to see if it gives us
the right angle on the East Tower?

15:52.868 --> 15:54.620
Yeah, yeah, come on over!

15:54.620 --> 15:58.165
Yeah, I-I mean, you get a good
vantage point from over here.

15:58.624 --> 16:00.709
Everybody looks so small.

16:00.709 --> 16:02.878
You could pretend that
they're not even people.

16:02.878 --> 16:06.048
They're just like little ants,
and you just squish 'em!

16:06.048 --> 16:07.967
You just squish 'em!

16:07.967 --> 16:10.219
But I can see your place, Oliver.

16:10.844 --> 16:12.221
Over there on 10.

16:12.221 --> 16:14.390
And, uh, Mabel,

16:14.390 --> 16:16.976
y-you used to live at 12, and...

16:17.893 --> 16:19.019
there's your friend's place.

16:20.771 --> 16:22.856
What's up with him and his lonely omelets?

16:22.856 --> 16:24.358
And why is he always staring?

16:24.984 --> 16:27.903
Well, who could say why
people do what they do.

16:27.903 --> 16:30.072
Anyway, a shot from here won't work

16:30.072 --> 16:32.658
because th-the windows are painted shut.

16:35.536 --> 16:37.121
Oh. Um...
- Ow.

